# CODEOWNERS for the Chapter 84 companion (the human side of quality).
#
# GitHub reads this file to decide who is automatically requested for review on a pull request, by path.
# It is the mechanical half of "who reviews what": the routing is automated so the right reviewer is
# pulled in without a human remembering to add them. It does NOT decide whether the review is any good --
# that is the substantive human act the rest of this chapter is about. A CODEOWNERS entry guarantees a
# reviewer is REQUESTED, never that they read the change.
#
# Syntax: a path pattern, then one or more owners (@user or @org/team). The LAST matching pattern wins,
# so order is specific-last. These are illustrative owner handles for the book, not real accounts.

# Default: everything is owned by the platform team unless a more specific rule below claims it.
*                                   @acme/platform-team

# tag::codeowners-rule[]
# The contract surface (public API) and the decision log get a stricter owner: changes here need a
# reviewer who owns the contract callers depend on and the rationale future teams will read.
/src/main/java/org/acme/review/     @acme/api-stewards
/docs/adr/                          @acme/architecture-council
# end::codeowners-rule[]

# The standard itself (the formatter config, the Checkstyle ruleset) is owned by the team that maintains
# the gate, so a change to the shared standard is reviewed deliberately rather than slipped in.
/config/                            @acme/platform-team
